[The Shiga (or Vero) cytotoxin is responsible for much of the disease caused by enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ and is encoded on a lambdoid bacteriophage. The phage forms stable lysogens in EHEC, and toxin is produced following induction of the lytic cycle of the phage replication, which can occur spontaneously or in response to a variety of stressors including many antimicrobials.

The toxin belongs to a family of protein toxins that contain one enzymatically active A moiety and 5 nontoxic B moieties that bind to the trisaccharide part of the glycosphingolipid Gb3 (1). An outbreak with a higher amount of HUS as a complication of EHEC as described here can be produced by several mechanisms, including:

1. A particular Shiga toxin genotype may be more cytotoxic by virtue of a hyperactive A component or better receptor binding of its B subunits.
2. Overexpression of the Shiga toxin, especially type 2 (2).
3. Enhanced exposure of the toxin-producing organism to the colon lining, as appeared to have occurred in the 2011 large Northern Germany-centered outbreak of the chimeric toxin-producing _E. coli_ O104:H4 that had genetic characteristics of both EHEC and enteroaggregative _E. coli_ (3)

Additionally, individuals may be more susceptible to complications of EHEC by expressing more receptor on target cells.

References:
1. Bergan J, Lingelem ABD, Simm R, et al: Shiga toxins. Toxicon 2012;60: 1085-1107
2. Neupane M, Abu-Ali GS, Mitra A, et al: Shiga toxin 2 overexpression in _Escherichia coli_ O157:H7 strains associated with severe human disease. Microbial Pathogenesis 2011;51: 466-470.
3. Bielaszewska M, Mellman A, Zhang W, et al: Characterization of the _Escherichia coli_ strain associated with an outbreak of haemolytic uremic syndrome in Germany, 2011: a microbiological study. Lancet Infect Dis 2011;11: 671-676. - Mod.LL]

